---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

// Content-mirror approach (snapshot, not MDX-import). Rationale:
//   - The canonical runbook lives at `docs/operations/SELFHOST.md` in the
//     repo (Worker B, FR-FBR-17). It is the operator-facing, terminal-side,
//     plain-text reference — it is updated post-launch as operators report
//     real-world incidents.
//   - This /docs/self-host page is the marketing-side introduction: "is
//     this for me, and what does the happy path look like?" — a snapshot
//     of the runbook's key sections (Prerequisites + Quickstart + required
//     env vars) plus a clear pointer to the canonical full runbook for
//     backup/restore, troubleshooting, and upgrade procedure depth.
//   - MDX-import was considered but rejected: a marketing page should be
//     editable for tone without changing the operator runbook, and the
//     runbook's literal bash blocks render better in a terminal context.
//
// The snapshot is taken from SELFHOST.md as of P4 Stage 2 freeze ping
// (2026-05-14T17:35Z). When SELFHOST.md changes substantively, refresh
// this page — see marketing/README.md Decision Log.
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Self-host"
  description="Run feedbackmonk on your own infrastructure with `docker compose up`. AGPL source, postgres + Rust api + nginx admin."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <h1>Self-host</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      feedbackmonk runs in your tenant via <code>docker compose up</code>.
      Same Rust binary as the SaaS tier, same migrations, same admin UI &mdash;
      no closed-source carve-out. The Self-host tier ships with no per-seat
      pricing and no feedback-volume cap.
    </p>
    <p class="snapshot-note" role="note">
      This page is a snapshot of the operator runbook. The canonical,
      operator-side version lives at
      <a href="https://github.com/feedbackmonk/feedbackmonk/blob/main/docs/operations/SELFHOST.md">
        <code>docs/operations/SELFHOST.md</code>
      </a>
      in the repo &mdash; refer to it for the full troubleshooting matrix,
      cron + systemd backup recipes, and upgrade procedure.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section aria-labelledby="who-heading">
    <h2 id="who-heading">Who is this for</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>You'd prefer your users' feedback never touch our servers.</li>
      <li>You already operate Docker on a VPS or Kubernetes cluster.</li>
      <li>You want predictable cost (one container stack, one postgres) instead of per-seat SaaS billing.</li>
      <li>You're comfortable with AGPL: modifications you ship must be made available under AGPL.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="prereq-heading">
    <h2 id="prereq-heading">Prerequisites</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th scope="col">Requirement</th><th scope="col">Version</th><th scope="col">Why</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Docker Engine</td>
          <td>24+ (Compose v2)</td>
          <td>Stack uses Compose v2 profiles + service-completed dependency conditions.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>RAM</td>
          <td>1 GB min / 2 GB recommended</td>
          <td>postgres + Rust api + nginx, plus a transient Rust build on first <code>up --build</code>.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Disk</td>
          <td>5 GB</td>
          <td>~80 MB api image, ~25 MB nginx, ~250 MB postgres data per 10k feedback rows. Add backup headroom.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Open ports</td>
          <td>1 (default 14304)</td>
          <td>Operator-facing admin edge. Postgres + api are not host-exposed by default.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>TLS proxy</td>
          <td>optional</td>
          <td>Stack speaks HTTP only. Production deployments terminate TLS upstream (Caddy / nginx / Cloudflare Tunnel).</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="quickstart-heading">
    <h2 id="quickstart-heading">Quickstart</h2>
    <pre><code>{`# 1. Clone the repo:
git clone https://github.com/feedbackmonk/feedbackmonk.git
cd feedbackmonk/deploy/docker

# 2. Copy the env template and edit four required values:
cp .env.example .env
\${EDITOR:-vim} .env
#   DATABASE_URL=postgres://feedbackmonk:<your-password>@db:5432/feedbackmonk
#   FEEDBACKMONK_PUBLIC_URL=https://feedback.example.com
#   FEEDBACKMONK_SESSION_SECRET=<openssl rand -hex 32>
#   POSTGRES_PASSWORD=<same as in DATABASE_URL>

# 3. Bring up the stack (first run builds the Rust image — 5-15 min cold):
docker compose up -d

# 4. Verify health:
curl http://localhost:14304/health/ready
# HTTP 200 with: {"status":"ok","db_connected":true,...}`}</code></pre>
    <p>
      If <code>/health/ready</code> returns 200 with
      <code>db_connected: true</code>, you're live. Visit
      <code>http://localhost:14304/</code> in a browser &mdash; you'll see
      the admin sign-in screen.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="env-heading">
    <h2 id="env-heading">Required environment variables</h2>
    <p>
      The canonical catalog &mdash; every var, with code line references and
      security-sensitivity flags &mdash; lives at
      <a href="https://github.com/feedbackmonk/feedbackmonk/blob/main/docs/operations/SELFHOST_ENV.md">
        <code>docs/operations/SELFHOST_ENV.md</code>
      </a>
      (Contract&nbsp;C21). The four required ones:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th scope="col">Var</th><th scope="col">Notes</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>DATABASE_URL</code></td>
          <td><code>postgres://USER:PASS@db:5432/feedbackmonk</code>. Host <code>db</code> is the compose service name &mdash; keep it.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>FEEDBACKMONK_PUBLIC_URL</code></td>
          <td>Customer-facing base URL. No trailing slash. Must match the URL operators actually visit (verify-email links use this verbatim).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>FEEDBACKMONK_SESSION_SECRET</code></td>
          <td>64 hex chars (32 bytes). Generate with <code>openssl rand -hex 32</code>. Rotating it invalidates all admin sessions.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>POSTGRES_PASSWORD</code></td>
          <td>Must match the password inside <code>DATABASE_URL</code>.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      The <code>.env.example</code> ships sensible defaults for ~16 optional vars
      (logging format, mailer selection, token TTLs, anon rate-limit, SMTP).
      Uncomment lines in <code>.env</code> to override.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="ops-heading">
    <h2 id="ops-heading">Operations</h2>

    <h3>Backup</h3>
    <p>Daily gzipped <code>pg_dump</code> via the bundled helper:</p>
    <pre><code>{`cd deploy/docker
mkdir -p backups
./backup.sh > backups/feedbackmonk-$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M%S).sql.gz`}</code></pre>
    <p>
      Cron / systemd-timer recipes are in
      <a href="https://github.com/feedbackmonk/feedbackmonk/blob/main/docs/operations/SELFHOST.md#4-backup-and-restore">SELFHOST.md §4</a>.
    </p>

    <h3>Restore (destructive)</h3>
    <p>
      The dump is <code>--clean --if-exists</code> &mdash; restoring drops
      and recreates every object. The helper requires confirmation:
    </p>
    <pre><code>{`gunzip -c backups/feedbackmonk-20260514.sql.gz | ./restore.sh
# type 'yes' at the prompt. Add --force for non-TTY DR drills.`}</code></pre>

    <h3>Upgrade</h3>
    <pre><code>{`git pull
cd deploy/docker
./backup.sh > backups/pre-upgrade-$(date +%Y%m%d).sql.gz
docker compose build
docker compose up -d`}</code></pre>
    <p>
      Every <code>docker compose up</code> runs the <code>migrate</code>
      init-container, which calls <code>sqlx migrate run</code> &mdash;
      idempotent on a fresh start, applies only new migrations on upgrade.
      Skipping or rolling back migrations is not supported; restore from
      backup if a migration fails.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="defends-heading">
    <h2 id="defends-heading">What defends this contract</h2>
    <p>
      The <em>selfhost-compose-smoke</em> Verification Oracle has three probes:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Probe A</strong> &mdash; yaml-lint of <code>docker-compose.yml</code>.</li>
      <li>
        <strong>Probe B</strong> &mdash; every env-var the compose stack references
        must exist in the canonical C21 catalog
        (<code>SELFHOST_ENV.md</code>). Catches "code added a var, docs didn't"
        drift before it reaches an operator.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Probe C</strong> &mdash; <code>--full</code> clean-state smoke:
        <code>docker compose down -v &amp;&amp; up -d</code>, wait for
        <code>/health/ready</code>, assert 200 with
        <code>db_connected: true</code>.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The oracle ran GREEN at the freeze ping for this page (P4 Stage 2,
      2026-05-14).
    </p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="agpl-heading">
    <h2 id="agpl-heading">License + source</h2>
    <p>
      feedbackmonk is <strong>AGPL-3.0-or-later</strong>. The Self-host tier
      receives identical releases to SaaS; there is no proprietary fork.
      Source: <a href="https://github.com/feedbackmonk/feedbackmonk">github.com/feedbackmonk/feedbackmonk</a>
      (org registration pending PF-REGISTER-01).
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

